e=\"text-align:center;\"|10\n|-\n| US ''Billboard'' [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\n|-\n| US ''Billboard'' [[Top Rap Albums]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n| US [[Kid Albums]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|8\n|-\n| US Soundtracks\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|}\n\n===Score===\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Rio\n| type       = Film\n| artist     = [[John Powell (film composer)|John Powell]]\n| cover      =\n| border     = yes\n| alt        = The word \"RIO\" in blue, yellow, and orange letters, with the \"R\" styled to resemble a bird's head.\n| released   = {{Start date|2011|04|19}}\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Film score|Score]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=47|s=04}}\n| label      = [[Var\u00e8se Sarabande]]\n| producer   =\n| chronology = [[John Powell (composer)|John Powell]] film scores\n| prev_title = [[Mars Needs Moms]]\n| prev_year  = 2011\n| next_title = [[Kung Fu Panda 2 (soundtrack)|Kung Fu Panda 2]]\n| next_year  = 2011\n}}\n\nThe [[film score]] of ''Rio'' was composed by [[John Powell (composer)|John Powell]] and was released on April 19, 2011, by [[Var\u00e8se Sarabande Records]].<ref name=\"iTunes\">{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/rio-original-motion-picture/id429214902 |title=Rio (Original Motion Picture Score) |work=iTunes |accessdate=April 22, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"FilmMusicReporter\">{{cite news |url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2011/03/24/rio-score-album-details |accessdate=April 22, 2011 |title='Rio' Score Album Details |newspaper=Film Music Reporter |date=March 24, 2011}}</ref>\n\n;Track listing\n{{Track listing\n| total_length  = 47:04\n| all_writing     = John Powell except where noted\n| title1        = Morning Routine\n| length1       = 2:23\n| title2        = Meet Tulio\n| length2       = 2:55\n| title3        = Great Big Momma Bird\n| length3       = 2:47\n| title4        = Paradise Concern\n| length4       = 1:59\n| title5        = Bagged and Missing\n| length5       = 2:09\n| title6        = Locked Up\n| length6       = 2:10\n| title7        = Chained Chase\n| length7       = 2:35\n| title8        = Bedtime Flyers\n| length8       = 2:58\n| title9        = Idiot Glider\n| length9       = 1:56\n| title10       = Juicy Little Mango\n| length10      = 2:27\n| title11       = Umbrellas of Rio\n| length11      = 2:27\n| title12       = Motorbike\n| length12      = 1:23\n| title13       = Bird Fight\n| length13      = 1:03\n| title14       = Birds Moved\n| length14      = 2:33\n| title15       = Heimlich\n| length15      = 2:31\n| title16       = Birdnapped\n| length16      = 3:37\n| title17       = Rio Airport\n| length17      = 4:24\n| title18       = Flying\n| length18      = 2:43\n| title19       = Market Forro\n| note19        = written by [[Carlinhos Brown]] and Mikael Mutti\n| length19      = 2:11\n}}\n\n==Release==\nThe world premiere of ''Rio'' took place on March 22, 2011, at a [[Cin\u00e9polis]] theater in [[Lagoa, Rio de Janeiro]].<ref name=\"BrazilPremiere\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/animated-3d-film-rio-premieres-in-brazil-favela-2254194.html |title=Animated 3D film 'Rio' premieres in Brazil favela |work=The Independent |location=UK |date=March 26, 2011 |accessdate=June 1, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Lagoa\" /> The United States premiere was on April 10, 2011, at [[Grauman's Chinese Theatre]] in Hollywood, California, and was released throughout the country five days later.<ref name=\"LAPremiere\">{{cite news |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/04/11/last-weekends-events-_n_847623.html |title=Last Weekend's Events: A Red Tie Affair, 'Rio' Premiere, and GLAAD Media Awards |work=Huffington Post |location=USA |date=April 11, 2011 |accessdate=June 1, 2011 |first=Nicole |last=Larson}}</ref> Since May 2009, it had been scheduled to be released in the United States on April 8, 2011, but in December 2010, it was rescheduled a week later to April 15, 2011.<ref>{{cite press release|author1=Twentieth Century Fox|title=New Blue Sky Animated Feature Film Announced \u201cRIO\u201d Opens April 8, 2011|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20090512006239/en/Blue-Sky-Animated-Feature-Film-Announced-%E2%80%9CRIO%E2%80%9D|publisher=Business Wire|accessdate=April 17, 2017|date=May 12, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=New Dates & Changes|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com:80/schedule/?view=changes&p=.htm|publisher=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=April 17, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101225053335/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/schedule/?view=changes&p=.htm|archivedate=December 25, 2010|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Marketing===\nIn April 2011, Oreo announced its special edition Oreo cookies with blue cream in promotion of the film. The promotion included stickers inside each package of cookies. Two types of contest were also announced: first, by completing an album of stickers, consumers could win three movie passes and medium snack bar combos; second, by finding winning stickers in packages with prizes including a trip to Rio de Janeiro, backpacks, cinema passes for a year, and 3D glasses. The promotion ended on May 30, 2011.<ref>{{cite news |title=Concurso Promo Oreo, gana paquetes de cine, viaje a Rio, mochilas y m\u00e1s |url=http://www.pe.promogana.net/2011/04/concurso-promo-oreo-gana-paquetes-de.html |accessdate=September 16, 2011 |newspaper=Promo Gana \u2013 Per\u00fa |date=April 8, 2011}}</ref> The promotion is available in Ecuador, Peru, and Colombia.{{Citation needed|date=August 2012}}\n\nOn January 27, 2011, [[Rovio Entertainment|Rovio Mobile]] announced a partnership with [[20th Century Fox]] to promote the film. The game ''[[Angry Birds Rio]]'' was released in March 2011 on the [[Android Market]] and the [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] [[App Store (iOS)|App Store]] with 50 levels. Rovio released more levels throughout 2011.<ref>{{cite news |last=Warne |first=Alex |title=Angry Birds Going Big Time |url=http://dailynewspulse.com/angry-birds-going-big-time/222346 |accessdate=September 16, 2011 |newspaper=Daily News Pulse |date=January 29, 2011}}</ref> With the DVD and Blu-ray release, Rovio and 20th Century Fox announced that they were going to start selling Rio Plush Toys in the Angry Birds Online Store and the DVD and Blu-ray comes with a code for 15 Hidden Levels, along with 3 Angry Birds Rio Videos. Also, [[McDonald's]] ran a promotion with Rio toys in their Happy Meals.<ref name=\"Angry Birds Rio DVD Bonus Levels and Plush Toys\">{{cite web |last=Team |first=Angry Birds |title=RIO plush toys and DVD wing their way into stores! |url=http://www.rovio.com/index.php?mact=Blogs,cntnt01,showentry,0&cntnt01entryid=78&cntnt01returnid=58 |work=Angry Birds Rio |accessdate=August 3, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2011, the [[Motion Picture Association of America|MPAA]] gave the film a PG rating for \"mild off-color humor\". The producers, displeased by this rating, resubmitted an edited version of the film to the ratings board one month later, and the MPAA changed the film to a G rating.<ref>{{cite news |last=Subers |first=Ray |title=MPAA Ratings: 'Kung Fu Panda 2,' 'Rio,' 'Arthur' and More |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3115&p=.htm |accessdate=September 15, 2011 |newspaper=Box Office Mojo |publisher=IMDb |date=March 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\nAs a tribute to the country where most of the story is set and where the director was born, ''Rio'' was first released for home video in Brazil, on both DVD and [[Blu-ray]], on July 7, 2011.<ref name=\"RioBrazilRelease\">{{cite news |title=Coletiva de imprensa com Carlos Saldanha no Rio de Janeiro |url=https://www.facebook.com/notes/cinnamon-comunica%C3%A7%C3%A3o/coletiva-de-imprensa-com-carlos-saldanha-no-rio-de-janeiro/238908306137596 |accessdate=July 16, 2011 |author=Comunica\u00e7\u00e3o, Cinnamon |date=July 4, 2011 |language=Portuguese}}</ref> The North American release date was August 2, 2011,<ref name=\"ComingSoon\">{{cite news |title=Rio Hits Blu-ray and DVD on August 2 |url=https://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=78672 |accessdate=June 17, 2011 |work=ComingSoon.net |date=June 15, 2011}}</ref> and the Australian release date was September 28, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Podmore|first1=Scott|title=Lively time in vibrant Rio|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/travel/world/lively-time-in-vibrant-rio/news-story/b71366769950e784e9a729487a61d2cb?nk=06baba470b40b5097ac4494c88badc1e-1482776615|website=The Herald Sun|accessdate=26 December 2016}}</ref> As of June 2014, a total of 12 million Blu-ray and DVD units had been sold worldwide.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Graser|first1=Marc|title=Fox Takes Digital Retail Partners on Road for \u2018Rio 2\u2032|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/fox-takes-digital-retail-partners-on-road-for-rio-2-1201246717/|accessdate=June 30, 2014|work=Variety|date=June 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\n''Rio'' is available in 4 different packages: a 4-disc \"Party Edition\" combination package (3D Blu-ray, Blu-ray, DVD, and Digital Copy), a 3-disc \"Party Edition\" combination package (Blu-ray, DVD, and Digital Copy), a 2-disc \"Party Edition\" combination package (DVD and Digital Copy), and a single disc DVD.<ref name=\"ComingSoon\" /><ref name=\"MovieWeb\">{{cite news |last=Gallagher |first=Brian |title=Rio Blu-ray and DVD Arrive August 2nd |url=http://www.movieweb.com/news/rio-blu-ray-and-dvd-arrive-august-2nd |accessdate=June 17, 2011 |work=MovieWeb.com |date=June 15, 2011}}</ref> The \"Digital Copy\" included with the 3-disc combination package is a separate disc that allows users to download a copy of the film to a computer through [[iTunes]] or [[Windows Media Player]] software. The 3-disc combination package also comes with an hour of bonus features.<ref name=\"MovieWeb\" /><ref name=\"Blu-ray.com\">{{cite news |last=Katz |first=Josh |title=Rio Blu-ray |url=http://www.blu-ray.com/news/?id=6676 |accessdate=June 17, 2011 |date=June 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Video games===\n{{Infobox video game\n|title=Rio (video game)\n|image=\n|developer=[[Eurocom]] (Consoles)<br />THQ (DS)\n|director=\n|producer=\n|composer=\n|publisher= [[THQ]]\n|platforms=[[Nintendo DS]], [[PlayStation 3]], [[Wii]], [[Xbox 360]]\n|released= '''Nintendo DS, PlayStation 3, Wii & Xbox 360'''{{vgrelease|NA|April 12, 2011|AUS|April 7, 2011|EU|April 8, 2011}}\n|modes= [[Single-player]], [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]]\n|genre= [[Party video game|Party]] <br />[[Music video games|Musical Platform]] (Nintendo DS)\n}}\nA video game based on the film was released on April 12, 2011, by THQ, for the [[Wii]], [[Nintendo DS]], [[PlayStation 3]], and the [[Xbox 360]].<ref name=\"GameStop\">{{cite web |title=Rio by THQ |url=http://www.gamestop.com/xbox-360/games/rio/90273 |work=Rio |accessdate=July 14, 2011}}</ref> Another game, ''[[Angry Birds Rio]]'', was released in March 2011 for various mobile and desktop systems.<ref name=\"ABRio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/218181/angry_birds_rio_release_teams_with_hollywood.html|title='Angry Birds Rio' Release Teams With Hollywood|author=Paul Suarez|work=PCWorld.com|date=2011-01-29|accessdate=2011-02-04| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110205124337/http://www.pcworld.com/article/218181/angry_birds_rio_release_teams_with_hollywood.html| archivedate=February 5, 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n====Reception (Rio)====\nThe game received mixed reception, with, for lowest to highest, Metacritic at 60 out of 100 based on 16 reviews for the Xbox 360 version,<ref>https://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-360/rio</ref> and 65 out of 100 based on 8 reviews for the PlayStation 3 version.<ref>https://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-3/rio</ref> And in GameRankings, 40.00% for the Wii version, 58.00% for the Nintendo DS version, 64.73% for the Xbox 360 version, and 71.67% for the PlayStation 3.\n\n==Rio: The 4-D Experience==\n''Rio: The 4-D Experience'' is a 12-minute [[4D film]] shown at various 4-D theatres over the world. Produced by [[SimEx-Iwerks]], it premiered on September 27, 2013 at the [[San Diego Zoo]] 4-D Theater.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sandiegozoo.org/rio/|title=Rio The 4-D Experience|website=San Diego Zoo}}</ref> Since May 24, 2014, it is being shown at the 5D Cinema at the revived [[Kentucky Kingdom]]. Since July 2014, it is being shown at the 4D Special FX Theater at [[Moody Gardens]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.moodygardens.com/attractions/4d_special_fx_theater/4d_schedule/|title=Virtual Reality Theater - 4D Special FX Theater - Interactive Movie Theater - Special Effects Theaters|website=www.moodygardens.com}}</ref> And since October 25, 2014, it is being shown at the [[Roxy Theatre (Warner Bros. Movie World)|Roxy Theatre]] at [[Warner Bros. Movie World]].<ref>movieworld.com.au/rides-and-attractions/family-entertainment/rio-4d.aspx</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''Rio'' made $143,619,809 in North America, along with $341,015,951 in other territories for a total of $484,635,760 worldwide, becoming the 13th highest-grossing film of 2011<ref>{{cite web |title=2011 WORLDWIDE GROSSES |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?view2=worldwide&yr=2011&p=.htm |work=Box Office Mojo |publisher=IMDb |accessdate=April 23, 2012}}</ref> and the 107th highest-grossing film of all time.<ref name=\"BoxOfficeMojo\">{{cite web |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=rio.htm |title=Rio (2011) |work=Box Office Mojo |publisher=IMDb |accessdate=September 2, 2011}}</ref> It was the first film of 2011 to pass the $400-million mark.\n\n====North America====\n''Rio'' debuted with $39,225,962 during its opening weekend on approximately 6,400 screens at 3,826 theaters. It ranked No. 1 at the box office surpassing the other new wide release, ''[[Scream 4]]'', which ranked #2.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3142&p=.htm |title=Weekend Report: 'Rio' Leads, 'Scream' Bleeds |first=Brandon |last=Gray |publisher=IMDb |work=Box Office Mojo |date=April 17, 2011 |accessdate=April 18, 2011}}</ref> This was the highest-grossing opening weekend of 2011 that far, finishing the year at sixteenth.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?view2=opening&yr=2011&p=.htm |title=2011 OPENING GROSSES |publisher=IMDb |work=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=April 18, 2011}}</ref> It also scored the largest opening weekend in April for an animated feature, and the sixth largest in April overall.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/alltime/weekends/month/?mo=04&p=.htm |title=TOP OPENING WEEKENDS BY MONTH |publisher=IMDb |work=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=June 8, 2011}}</ref> On its second weekend (Easter weekend) it retained first place at the box office, dropping only 33% to $26.3 million, therefore surpassing that weekend's releases, Tyler Perry's ''[[Madea's Big Happy Family (film)|Madea's Big Happy Family]]'' ($25.1 million), ''[[Water for Elephants (film)|Water for Elephants]]'' ($16.8 million), and ''[[African Cats]]'' ($6 million), which ranked second, third, and sixth, respectively.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?view=&yr=2011&wknd=16&p=.htm |title=April 22\u201324, 2011 Weekend |publisher=IMDb |work=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=April 18, 2011}}</ref> ''Rio''{{'}}s income of $143.6 million made it Blue Sky's second lowest box office result at the time, surpassing only ''[[Robots (2005 film)|Robots]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3165&p=.htm|title=Animation Deceptively Strong So Far in 2011 - Box Office Mojo|website=boxofficemojo.com}}</ref> and the 18th highest-grossing film of the year in North America.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?yr=2011&p=.htm|title=2011 Yearly Box Office Results - Box Office Mojo|website=boxofficemojo.com}}</ref>\n\n====Other territories====\nOn its first weekend overseas (the weekend before its release in North America) it topped the box office with $54.9 million from 11,714 screens in 72 countries.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3136&p=.htm |title=Around-the-World Roundup: 'Rio' Livens Up Foreign Box Office |first=Ray |last=Subers |publisher=IMDb |work=Box Office Mojo |date=April 13, 2011 |accessdate=April 25, 2011}}</ref> On its second weekend it earned $55.4 million, still on top of the overseas box office<ref>{{cite news |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3144&p=.htm |title=Around-the-World Roundup: 'Rio' Continues to Soar Overseas |first=Ray |last=Subers |publisher=IMDb |work=Box Office Mojo |date=April 17, 2011 |accessdate=April 25, 2011}}</ref> and on its third weekend it remained at the summit of the box office, grossing an estimated $44.3 million. It therefore marked the second film that succeeded in topping the overseas box office three times in 2011, joining ''[[Tangled]]'', although it is the only one that did it on three consecutive weekends.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3147&p=.htm |title=Around-the-World Roundup: 'Rio' Reigns Again, 'Fast Five,' 'Thor' Duke It Out in Australia |first=Ray |last=Subers |publisher=IMDb |work=Box Office Mojo |date=April 26, 2011 |accessdate=April 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn Brazil, the film's main setting and Saldanha's homeland, ''Rio'' was the largest release ever with over 1,000 screens.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fox confirma estreia recorde de \"Rio\" no Brasi|url=http://ultimosegundo.ig.com.br/cultura/cinema/fox+confirma+estreia+recorde+de+rio+no+brasil/n1300033422291.html|publisher=Ultimo Segundo|accessdate=March 31, 2014|date=April 7, 2011}}</ref> Its opening weekend gross of $8.4 million was the biggest ever for an American film<ref>{{cite news |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3136&p=.htm |title=Around-the-World Roundup: 'Rio' Livens Up Foreign Box Office |first=Ray |last=Subers |publisher=IMDb |work=Box Office Mojo |date=April 13, 2011 |accessdate=April 18, 2011}}</ref> (surpassed one year later by ''[[Madagascar 3: Europe's Most Wanted]]''). On its second weekend it earned $7.2 million, falling just 14% from its opening. It then delivered the highest-grossing third weekend in history with $6.3 million (a 12% decline).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3147&p=.htm |title=Around-the-World Roundup: 'Rio' Reigns Again, 'Fast Five,' 'Thor' Duke It Out in Australia |first=Brandon |last=Gray |publisher=IMDb |work=Box Office Mojo |date=April 26, 2011 |accessdate=May 4, 2011}}</ref> ''Rio'' finished 2011 with a final gross of $36.8 million (R$68.7 million), the second highest income of the year after ''[[The Twilight Saga: Breaking Dawn \u2013 Part 1]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://oca.ancine.gov.br/media/SAM/Informes/2011/Informe_Anual_2011.pdf |title=INFORME DE  ACOMPANHAMENTO DO MERCADO: Filmes e Bilheterias, Resultados de 2011  |publisher=Ancine|language=Portuguese|format=PDF|page=6|date=January 11, 2012|accessdate=March 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Russia]] and the [[Commonwealth of Independent States|CIS]], it topped the box office with $11.3 million during its opening weekend (including weekday previews), surpassing ''Tangled'' for the largest all-time opening of a non-sequel animated feature. It earned $24.7 million in total, marking the fourth largest animated film of all time.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/intl/cis/yearly |title=Russia Box Office |publisher=IMDb |work=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=June 8, 2011}}</ref> In [[Venezuela]], it has earned $8 million, marking the second-highest-grossing film of all time behind ''Ice Age 3'' ($11.6 million).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/intl/venezuela/yearly/?yr=2011&p=.htm |title=Venezuela Yearly Box Office |publisher=IMDb |work=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=June 16, 2011}}</ref> In [[Uruguay]], it is the fourth highest-grossing film of all time with $754,820 after ''[[Titanic (1997 film)|Titanic]]'' ($2.1 million), ''[[Avatar (2009 film)|Avatar]]'' ($1.1 million), and ''Ice Age 3'' ($1 million).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/intl/uruguay/yearly/?yr=2011&p=.htm |title=Uruguay Yearly Box Office |publisher=IMDb |work=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=June 16, 2011}}</ref> In [[Peru]], grossing $3.8 million, it is the third-largest animated feature behind ''Ice Age 3'' and ''[[Shrek Forever After]]'', and the fourth highest-grossing film of all time behind these two and ''Avatar''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/intl/peru/yearly/?yr=2011&p=.htm |title=Peru Yearly Box Office |publisher=IMDb |work=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=June 16, 2011}}</ref> In [[India]], it grossed {{INR}}10,000,000 in three weeks making the biggest animated opener ever.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficeindia.co.in/rio-rises-to-greater-heights |title=Rio gets to Greater heights |publisher=Box Office India |accessdate=August 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n{{Anchor|Critics}}\n''Rio'' received positive reviews from film critics. The review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives the film a 72% rating based on 148 reviews, with an average rating of 6.4/10. The website's consensus is: \"This straightforward movie hits great heights thanks to its colorful visual palette, catchy music, and perfect vocal performances.\"<ref name=\"RottenTomatoes\" /> On [[Metacritic]], which assigns a normalized rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the film has an average score of 63 out of 100, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/rio |title=Rio |work=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=April 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[Owen Gleiberman]] of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave the film a mixed \"C\" rating; he praised the animation in ''Rio'' and its music, but later went on to say that the film is \"less a [[Pixar]]-level pleasure than a busy, frantic, and overstuffed dessert of a movie.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20481533,00.html |title=Rio |last=Gleiberman |first=Owen |work=Entertainment Weekly |accessdate=April 13, 2011}}</ref> Betsy Sharkey of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' gave the film a positive review, praising its comic action, voices and visuals.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2011/apr/15/entertainment/la-et-rio-20110415 |title='Rio' review |last=Sharkey |first=Betsy |work=Los Angeles Times |date=April 15, 2011 |accessdate=May 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=\"99%\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; vertical-align:bottom;\"\n|+ style=\"background: LightSteelBlue;\" | List of awards and nominations\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! Award\n! Category\n! Recipient(s)\n! Result\n|- style=\"border-top:2px solid gray;\"\n|-\n|-\n| [[84th Academy Awards]]\n| [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]], \"Real in Rio\"\n| [[S\u00e9rgio Mendes]]<br />[[Carlinhos Brown]]<br />[[Siedah Garrett]]\n| rowspan=2 {{Nom}}\n|-\n| style=\"border-top:10px black\" rowspan=\"8\" | [[Annie Award]]s\n| [[Annie Award for Best Animated Feature|Best Animated Feature]]\n| Bruce Anderson<br /> John C. Donkin\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Annie Award#Individual achievement|Best Character Animation in an Animated Production]]\n| Jeff Gabor\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Patrik Puhala\n| rowspan=11 {{Nom}}\n|-\n| [[Annie Award#Individual achievement|Best Character Design in a Feature Production]]\n| Sergios Pablos\n|-\n| [[Annie Award#Individual achievement|Directing in an Animated Feature Production]]\n| [[Carlos Saldanha]]\n|-\n| [[Annie Award#Individual achievement|Best Music in an Animated Feature Production]]\n| Mikael Mutti<br />[[Siedah Garrett]]<br />[[Carlinhos Brown]]<br />[[S\u00e9rgio Mendes]]<br />[[John Powell (film composer)|John Powell]]\n|-\n| [[Annie Award#Individual achievement|Production Design in an Animated Feature Production]]\n| Thomas Cardone<br />Kyle MacNaughton<br />Peter Chan\n|-\n| [[Annie Award#Individual achievement|Best Voice Acting in an Animated Feature Production]]\n| [[Jemaine Clement]]\n|-\n| [[38th People's Choice Awards]]<ref>[http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2011/11/08/nominations-announced-for-the-peoples-choice-awards-2012/109957/ \"Nominations Announced for the 'People's Choice Awards 2012'\"]. ''TV by the Numbers''. Retrieved August 25, 2012.</ref>\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Favorite Movie Animated Voice\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Anne Hathaway]]\n|-\n| [[2011 Teen Choice Awards]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Teen Choice Awards Nominees \u2013 2011 List |url=http://www.nationalledger.com/pop-culture-news/teen-choice-awards-nominees-113674.shtml |accessdate=July 1, 2011 |newspaper=The National Ledger |date=June 29, 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[2012 Kids' Choice Awards]]\n| Favorite Animated Movie\n!\n|-\n| [[38th Saturn Awards]]\n| Best Animated Film\n!\n|-\n|[[10th Visual Effects Society Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.visualeffectssociety.com/ayear/10th-annual-ves-awards|title=10th Annual VES Awards|work=visual effects society|accessdate=December 31, 2017}}</ref>\n|Outstanding Animated Character in an Animated Feature Motion Picture\n| Diana Diriwaechter, Sang Jun Lee, Sergio Pablos, Aamir Tarin\n|}\n\n==Sequel==\n{{Main|Rio 2}}\nA sequel, titled ''[[Rio 2]]'', was released on April 11, 2014. Carlos Saldanha, the creator and director of the first film, returned as director. All the main cast, including Anne Hathaway, Jesse Eisenberg, Jemaine Clement, Jamie Foxx, will.i.am, Tracy Morgan, George Lopez, Jake T. Austin, Leslie Mann, and Rodrigo Santoro, reprised their roles. New cast includes [[Andy Garc\u00eda]], [[Bruno Mars]], [[Kristin Chenoweth]], [[Rita Moreno]], [[Amandla Stenberg]], [[Rachel Crow]], [[Pierce Gagnon]], and [[Natalie Morales (journalist)|Natalie Morales]]. The sequel follows Blu, Jewel and their three kids on a venture into the [[Amazon rainforest|Amazon]] where they try to live like real birds. Eventually, they find Jewel's long-lost father Eduardo, who is in hiding with a tribe of other [[Spix's macaw]]. At first everything seems perfect, but Blu is having trouble adapting to the wild. Eventually, they discover that the Amazon is under threat, and that Blu and Jewel's old nemesis, Nigel the cockatoo, is back for revenge.<ref name=\"Cast\">{{cite web|url=http://blueskystudios.com/blog/entry/official-rio2-casting-press-release/ |title=Twentieth Century Fox Animation Announces Rio 2 Casting |publisher=Blue Sky Studios |date=February 22, 2013 |accessdate=February 22, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"Variety\">\n{{cite news\n| url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118003473\n| title=Fox, Blue Sky drawn to 'Rio'\n| last=Siegel\n| first=Tatiana\n| date=May 11, 2009\n| work=Variety\n| access-date=January 20, 2010\n}}</ref>\n\n<!--<ref name=\"BlueSky\">\n{{cite press release\n| title=Blue Sky's next feature 'Rio' on its way in April 2011\n| work=Blue Sky Studios\n| date=May 14, 2009\n| url=http://blueskystudios.com/content/company-pressrelease.php?id=30\n| access-date=October 7, 2010\n}}</ref> -->\n\n<ref name=\"CinemaBlend\">\n{{cite web\n| url=https://www.cinemablend.com/new/Neil-Patrick-Harris-Takes-Anne-Hathaway-To-Rio-15351.html\n| title=Neil Patrick Harris Takes Anne Hathaway To Rio\n| last=Gomez\n| first=Tim\n| date=October 22, 2009\n| work=Cinema Blend\n| access-date=January 20, 2010\n}}</ref>\n\n<!--<ref name=\"Blastr\">\n{{cite news\n| url=http://blastr.com/2009/06/why-the-animated-rio-is-i.php\n| title=Why the animated Rio is Ice Age director Carlos Saldanha's dream project\n| last=Topel\n| first=Fred\n| date=June 8, 2009\n| work=Blastr\n| accessdate=January 20, 2010\n}}</ref>-->\n\n<ref name=\"Lagoa\">\n{{cite news\n| last=Azevedo\n| first=Erika\n| url=http://oglobo.globo.com/cultura/mat/2011/03/22/na-lagoa-astros-de-hollywood-falam-de-sua-experiencia-na-animacao-rio-924062651.asp\n| title=In Lagoa, Hollywood stars talk about the experience in the animation 'Rio'\n| language=Portuguese\n| work=O Globo\n| date=March 22, 2011\n| access-date=March 27, 2011\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"RottenTomatoes\">\n{{cite news\n| url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/rio\n| title=Rio\n| work= [[Rotten Tomatoes]]\n| publisher= [[Fandango Media]]\n| access-date=April 6, 2011\n}}</ref>\n\n<!--<ref name=\"Reviews\">\n{{cite news\n| last=Movies News Reviews\n| first=Reviews\n| title=Rio\n| url=http://www.streamingwatchfreemoviesonline.com/watch-rio-2011-online-free-watch-free-movies-online\n| access-date=April 18, 2011\n| date=April 18, 2011\n}}</ref>-->\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Rio (2011 film)}}\n{{Wikiquote|Rio (film)}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.rio-themovie.com}}\n* {{IMDb title|1436562|Rio}}\n* {{bcdb title|110636|Rio}}\n* {{Allmovie title|489380|Rio}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|rio|Rio}}\n* {{Metacritic film|rio|Rio}}\n* {{Mojo title|rio|Rio}}\n{{Portal bar|Cartoon|Animation}}\n{{Blue Sky Studios}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rio (Film)}}\n[[Category:2011 films]]\n[[Category:2011 3D films]]\n[[Category:2011 computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:2010s children's comedy films]]\n[[Category:2010s adventure comedy films]]\n[[Category:2010s American animated films]]\n[[Category:2010s children's animated films]]\n[[Category:American children's animated adventure films]]\n[[Category:American children's animated comedy films]]\n[[Category:American computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Animated adventure films]]\n[[Category:Animated comedy films]]\n[[Category:Animated films about birds]]\n[[Category:Animated musical films]]\n[[Category:Brazil in fiction]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Fictional birds]]\n[[Category:Fictional parrots]]\n[[Category:Films about animal rights]]\n[[Category:Films about cruelty to animals]]\n[[Category:Films featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:Films set in Brazil]]\n[[Category:Films set in Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Films set in Rio de Janeiro (city)]]\n[[Category:Films set in South America]]\n[[Category:Films using computer-generated imagery]]\n[[Category:Portuguese-language films]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox films]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox animated films]]\n[[Category:Blue Sky Studios films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Carlos Saldanha]]\n[[Category:Films scored by John Powell]]\n[[Category:Annie Award winners]]\n[[Category:3D animated films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Rio\n| image          = Rio2011Poster.jpg\n| alt            = A blue Spix's macaw wearing a yellow scarf is surrounded by other birds and animals from the film. They sit on a sandy beach with beachgoing tourists in the background, facing away. The weather is mostly sunny, with one cloud in the sky. The text reads \"From the creators of ''Ice Age'': RIO\"\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Carlos Saldanha]]\n| producer       = Bruce Anderson<br />John C. Donkin\n| screenplay     = [[Don Rhymer]]<br />[[Joshua Sternin]]<br />[[Jennifer Ventimilia|Jeffrey Ventimilia]]<br />[[Sam Harper]]\n| story          = Carlos Saldanha<br />Earl Richey Jones<br />Todd Jones\n| starring       = {{Plain list|\n* [[Anne Hathaway]]\n* [[Jesse Eisenberg]]\n* [[George Lopez]]\n* [[Jemaine Clement]]\n* [[Tracy Morgan]]\n* [[Leslie Mann]]\n* [[Will.i.am]] \n* [[Jamie Foxx]]\n}}<!-- DO NOT CHANGE THIS LIST, THIS IS ACCORDING TO THE CREDIT BLOCK ON THE POSTER! -->\n| music          = [[John Powell (composer)|John Powell]]\n| cinematography = Renato Falc\u00e3o\n| editing        = Harry Hitner\n| studio         = [[Blue Sky Studios]]<br />[[20th Century Fox Animation]]\n| distributor    = [[20th Century Fox]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2011|3|22|World premiere|2011|4|15|North America|ref1=<ref name=\"BrazilPremiere\" />}}<!-- Note: The first release dates, whether it was at a film festival or a public release, and the domestic release date should only be included in the parameter. See WP:FILMRELEASE. -->\n| runtime        = 96 minutes\n| country        = United States<!-- Please do not add Brazil here. Per Template:Infobox film, the country parameter is for the home country or the companies that are part of their home country. Blue Sky Studios and 20th Century Fox are American companies. -->\n| language       = English<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/rio-2011|website=BBFC|title=Rio (2011)|accessdate=November 14, 2017}}</ref>\n| budget         = $90 million<ref name=\"LABox\">{{cite news |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/entertainmentnewsbuzz/2011/04/box-office-rio-scream-4-conspirator.html |title=Movie Projector: 'Rio' should stifle 'Scream 4' |last=Kaufman |first=Amy |work=Los Angeles Times |publisher=Tribune Company |date=April 14, 2011 |accessdate=May 3, 2011}}</ref>\n| gross          = $484.6 million<!-- Please do not change it unless it says so on Box Office Mojo. Furthermore, if you change the number, also change the access date. --><ref name=\"BoxOfficeMojo\" />\n}}\n'''''Rio''''' is a 2011 American [[3D film|3D]] [[Computer animation|computer-animated]] [[musical film|musical]] [[Adventure film|adventure]]-[[comedy film]] produced by [[Blue Sky Studios]] and directed by [[Carlos Saldanha]]. The title refers to the Brazilian city of [[Rio de Janeiro]],<ref name=\"Variety\" /> where the film is set. The film features the voices of [[Jesse Eisenberg]], [[Anne Hathaway]], [[Leslie Mann]], [[Rodrigo Santoro]], [[Jemaine Clement]], [[George Lopez]], [[Tracy Morgan]] and [[Jamie Foxx]]. It tells the story of Blu (Eisenberg), a domesticated male [[Spix's macaw]] who is taken to Rio de Janeiro to mate with a free-spirited female Spix's macaw, Jewel (Hathaway). The two eventually fall in love, and together they have to escape from being smuggled by Nigel (Clement), a [[cockatoo]]. The theme song, \"Telling the World,\" was performed by [[Taio Cruz]].\n\nSaldanha developed his first story concept of ''Rio'' in 1995, in which a penguin is washed up in Rio. Saldanha learned of the production of the films ''[[Happy Feet]]'' (2006) and ''[[Surf's Up (film)|Surf's Up]]'' (2007), and changed the concept to involve macaws and their environments in Rio. He proposed his idea to [[Chris Wedge]] in 2006, and the project was set up at [[Blue Sky Studios|Blue Sky]]. The main voice actors were approached in 2009. During production, the crew visited Rio de Janeiro and also consulted with an expert on macaws at the [[Bronx Zoo]] to study their movements.\n\n''Rio'' premiered on March 22, 2011 in [[Lagoa, Rio de Janeiro]], followed by its general release on April 15, 2011 by [[20th Century Fox]]. The film received moderately positive reviews from film critics, who praised the visuals, voice acting and music. The film was also a box office success, grossing over $143 million in the United States and $484 million worldwide. The film was nominated for an [[Academy Awards|Oscar]] for [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] for the song \"Real in Rio\", but lost to the other nominee, \"[[Man or Muppet]]\" from ''[[The Muppets (film)|The Muppets]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nominees for the 84th Academy Awards |url=http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/84/nominees.html |work=Oscars.org |accessdate=February 1, 2012 |date=January 24, 2012}}</ref> A sequel, ''[[Rio 2]]'', was released on April 11, 2014.\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- NOTICE: PER WP:FILMPLOT, PLOT SUMMARIES IN FILM ARTICLES SHOULD BE KEPT BETWEEN 400-700 WORDS. -->\nIn [[Brazil]], various exotic birds are smuggled out of the country. In [[Moose Lake, Minnesota]], a crate with a male [[Spix's macaw]] hatchling falls out of a truck and is found by a little girl named Linda Gunderson, who names him Blu. Over the next 15 years,<ref name=\"TeleRhap\" /> Linda comes to own a bookstore. Highly tame and unable to fly because he is scared to, Blu is ridiculed frequently by the [[Canada goose|Canada geese]] that come by outside of Linda's bookstore.\n\nOne day, [[ornithology|ornithologist]] T\u00falio Monteiro invites Blu and Linda to [[Rio de Janeiro]] because Blu, who is the last known male of his species, needs to mate with the last known male macaw. Linda initially refuses, but later accepts and they fly to Rio. At T\u00falio's [[aviary]], Blu meets Roberto, a fiercely independent [[Spix's macaw]] male longing to flee back to the wilderness. The macaws are captured by Fernando, an orphaned boy, and a [[sulphur-crested cockatoo]] named Nigel, both of whom work for a group of smugglers led by Marcel, who wants to leave the country as soon as possible to secure a black market deal regarding Blu and Roberto.\n\nWhile Fernando has second thoughts about his actions, Nigel tells the macaws that he desires to exact revenge on \"pretty birds\" after his role on a television show had been replaced by a parakeet. However, because of Blu's familiarity with cages, they flee into the jungle. Fernando meets Linda and T\u00falio and helps them find the birds, while Blu and Roberto meet Rafael, a [[toco toucan]], who offers to take them to his [[bulldog]] friend, Luiz, to remove their leg chain.\n\nHe attempts to teach Blu how to fly, before they meet up with a [[red-crested cardinal]] named Pedro and his [[yellow canary]] friend Nico. Meanwhile, Nigel coerces a horde of thieving [[marmoset]]s led by Mauro to capture Blu and Roberto. Pedro and Nico then take the macaws to a Rio-style dance party, where they dance together and begin to fall in love, but encounter the marmosets in the process. The birds fight them off while the five escape on a [[tram]].\n\nFernando takes Linda and T\u00falio to the smugglers' hideout, where they discover the birds have already been moved out. Marcel explains that he will use the [[Rio Carnival]] parade to smuggle the birds to the airport, as the other streets have been blocked off for the festivities. Meanwhile, Blu and the others meet Luiz, who releases the chain holding Blu and Roberto. After the two get into a heated argument, they decide to go their separate ways.\n\nPedro and Nico then witness Nigel capturing Roberto. When Blu and Rafael learn of it, they rush to the carnival to rescue her. Meanwhile, Linda and T\u00falio have spotted the smugglers' parade float and organize a rescue attempt for the birds. As Linda and T\u00falio pose as dancers in [[Spix's macaw]] costumes, Nigel captures Blu and the group. Linda and T\u00falio are unable to stop the smugglers in time and Marcel's group takes off in a [[Short SC.7 Skyvan]].\n\nDuring the flight, Blu breaks out his cage using a fire extinguisher and releases the other captive birds. However, Nigel attacks the macaws, injuring Roberto's wing in the process. Blu sends Nigel flying into the plane's engine using the fire extinguisher, causing the plane to fall. The smugglers flee the plane. Unable to fly, Roberto falls out of the plane's open cargo hatch towards the ocean. Jumping out of the plane to rescue her, Blu finally discovers that he is able to fly as he and Roberto kiss, and he carries him to Linda and T\u00falio for help.\n\nLater, they adopt Fernando and live in the jungle to help protect the jungle from smugglers. Blu and Robero eventually raise three chicks named Mario, Luigi, and Toad together, and celebrate with Rafael, Nico, Pedro, Linda, Luiz, and T\u00falio. Meanwhile, Nigel survives the plane crash but is ridiculed for his loss of feathers by Mauro, and the smugglers are sent to prison.\n\n==Voice cast==\n* [[Jesse Eisenberg]] as Tyler Blu Gunderson, AKA: Blu, a male [[Spix's macaw]]<ref>{{cite news |title=The Real \"Rio\": True Story of a Spix's Macaw |url=http://www.dailykos.com/story/2012/02/15/1065030/-The-Real-Rio-True-Story-of-a-Spix-s-Macaw |accessdate=May 20, 2012 |newspaper=Daily Kos |date=February 15, 2012}}</ref> who was born in Rio de Janeiro but raised in [[Moose Lake, Minnesota]], after he was smuggled.\n* [[Anne Hathaway]] as Jewel, a female Spix's macaw from The Amazon Jungle, but was taken into Rio de Janeiro.\n* [[Will.i.am]] as Pedro, a [[red-crested cardinal]] who is Nico's best friend.\n* [[Jamie Foxx]] as Nico, a [[yellow canary]] who loves to [[samba]], and whose bottlecap hat functions as a tambourine.\n* [[George Lopez]] as Rafael, a romantic [[toco toucan]] fond of Carnival.\n* [[Tracy Morgan]] as Luiz, a [[bulldog]] who is Rafael's friend and a [[chainsaw]] expert who has a medical condition of drooling.\n* [[Jemaine Clement]] as Nigel, a sadistic [[sulphur-crested cockatoo]] who used to be a TV star, but was replaced by a Parakeet, causing him to have a  strong hatred for \"pretty birds.\"\n* [[Rodrigo Santoro]] as Dr. T\u00falio Monteiro, a Brazilian ornithologist. Santoro also voices a Soccer Announcer.\n* [[Leslie Mann]] as Linda Gunderson, a girl who discovered Blu after he was taken from Rio de Janeiro to Moose Lake and adopted him for 15 years.\n* [[Jake T. Austin]] as Fernando, Marcel's impoverished young assistant.\n* [[Jane Lynch]] as Alice, a [[Canada goose]] who is Chloe's sister.\n* [[Wanda Sykes]] as Chloe, a [[Canada goose]] who is Alice's sister.\n* Davi Vieira as Armando, one of Marcel's minions alongside Tipa.\n* [[Carlos Ponce]] as Marcel, Nigel's owner and the leader of a group of exotic bird smugglers.\n* [[Jeffrey Garcia]] as Tipa/Short-Tailed Bat.\n* [[Bebel Gilberto]] as Eva, a [[keel-billed toucan]] and Rafael's wife.\n* Bernardo de Paula as Kipo, a [[roseate spoonbill]], and Sylvio, the security guard at T\u00falio's aviary.\n* Francisco Ramos as Mauro (credited as \"Lead Marmoset\"), the leader of the [[marmoset]]s, his name wasn't mentioned in the film.\n\n==Production==\nSaldanha first had the idea for the film in 1995, involving a penguin being washed up on the beaches of Ipanema; it was changed to the current story after he learned of ''[[Happy Feet]]'' and ''[[Surf's Up (film)|Surf's Up]]'' (two other films involving penguins) being produced. He pitched the idea to Chris Wedge at Blue Sky in 2006.<ref name=\"TeleRhap\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/8398693/Rio-Brazilian-rhapsody.html |title=Rio: Brazilian rhapsody |first=Craig |last=McLean |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK |date=March 28, 2011 |issn=0307-1235 |oclc=49632006 |accessdate=May 1, 2011}}</ref> Saldanha showed the animators maps and books with geographic landmarks and measurements, from which they built a digital version of Rio. Later, a group of artists from the company visited Rio to see the various story locations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mb.com.ph/articles/312336/rio-director-pays-homage-hometown-with-new-animated-movie |title='Rio' director pays homage to hometown with new animated movie |first=Annie |last=Alejo |work=Manila Bulletin |date=April 1, 2011 |accessdate=May 1, 2011}}</ref> The animators also met with an expert on macaws at the [[Bronx Zoo]] to gain insight into their movement and personalities.<ref name=\"WSJCarlos\">{{cite news |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2011/04/14/director-carlos-saldanha-returns-home-with-rio/?mod=google_news_blog |title=Director Carlos Saldanha Returns Home with 'Rio' |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=April 14, 2011 |accessdate=May 1, 2011 |first=Julie |last=Steinberg}}</ref> Saldanha himself is a Brazilian from Rio de Janeiro; such elements of Brazilian culture and landmarks were also influenced from Saldanha growing up in Brazil.<ref name=\"WSJCarlos\"/>\n\nThe lead voice actors were approached in 2009.<ref name=\"TeleRhap\" /> Jemaine Clement was approached to do the film after seeing test shots of his character Nigel doing a speech from ''[[Flight of the Conchords (TV series)|Flight of the Conchords]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/arts-life/4857420/Another-feather-in-his-cap |title=Another feather in his cap |first=Tom |last=Cardy |work=Stuff.co.nz |date=April 7, 2011 |accessdate=May 1, 2011}}</ref> which was done prior to a script being finalized.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thisisfakediy.co.uk/articles/film/interview-jemaine-clement |title=Interview: Jemaine Clement|work=ThisIsFakeDIY.co.uk |date=March 30, 2011 |accessdate=May 1, 2011}}</ref> [[Neil Patrick Harris]] was supposed to voice Blu, but had other commitments outside production;<ref name=\"CinemaBlend\" /> he was later replaced by [[Jesse Eisenberg]]. Eisenberg was asked during the filming of ''[[The Social Network]]'' if he would do his voice recording on the weekends, and he agreed after reading the script, saying: \"It was the perfect antidote to get out of the mindset of my character in ''Social Network'' who was so severe, and in some ways so joyless.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2011/04/15/jesse-eisenberg-goes-from-facebook-to-rio |title=Jesse Eisenberg Goes from Facebook to 'Rio' |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=April 15, 2011 |accessdate=May 1, 2011 |first=Julie |last=Steinberg}}</ref>\n\nFor music, they brought on board [[S\u00e9rgio Mendes]] to act as music guru and online living library.<ref name=\"WSJCarlos\" /> He in turn was able to reach out to artists such as will.i.am and [[Carlinhos Brown]] to provide music for the film.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.boston.com/2011-04-10/ae/29404021_1_rio-fox-animation-division-ice-age |title='Ice Age' team goes to 'Rio' |first=Tom |last=Russo |work=Articles.Boston.com |date=April 11, 2011 |accessdate=May 1, 2011}}</ref>\n\nEisenberg and Anne Hathaway, who voiced Jewel, had acted together before when both were still teenagers, when they played siblings in the short-lived 1999 TV show ''[[Get Real (U.S. TV series)|Get Real]]''. Hathaway stated in an interview that she didn't see Eisenberg during production of ''Rio'' except \"socially throughout the process,\" but that she was \"very happy for all of his success.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Murray |first=Rebecca |title=Inside 'Rio' with Anne Hathaway, Jamie Foxx, and George Lopez |url=http://movies.about.com/od/rio/a/rio-cast-interview.htm |work=About.com |accessdate=September 16, 2011 |date=January 28, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110916205908/http://movies.about.com/od/rio/a/rio-cast-interview.htm |archivedate=September 16, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Music==\n\n===Soundtrack===\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Rio: Music from the Motion Picture\n| type       = [[Soundtrack]]\n| artist     = Various Artists\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|2011|03|29}} {{small|(Digital download)}}<br />April 5, 2011 {{small|(Audio CD)}}\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]], [[Latin music (genre)|Latin]], [[alternative hip hop]]\n| length     = 38:11\n| label      = [[Interscope Records|Interscope]], [[will.i.am Music Group]]\n| producer   = [[S\u00e9rgio Mendes]], [[John Powell (composer)|John Powell]]\n| chronology = [[Blue Sky Studios]] film soundtrack\n| prev_title = [[Ice Age: Dawn of the Dinosaurs]]\n| prev_year  = 2009\n| next_title = [[Ice Age: Continental Drift]]\n| next_year  = 2012\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Rio: Music from the Motion Picture\n | type        = Soundtrack\n | single1     = [[Telling the World]]\n | single1date = March 22, 2011\n}}\n}}\n\n\nOn March 18, 2011, [[Brazilians in the United Kingdom|Brazilian-English]] singer-songwriter [[Taio Cruz]] released a music video and theme song named \"Telling the World\" on YouTube for the soundtrack.<ref>{{cite web |title=Telling the World (From the Soundtrack to \"RIO\" the Movie) |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4JK_Lg8P7PU |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=September 16, 2011 |author=TaioCruzVEVO |date=March 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\n''Rio: Music from the Motion Picture'' was released in the United States by 20th Century Fox on March 29, 2011, for [[Music download|digital download]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Rio: Music From The Motion Picture |url=https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B004SF30HI |publisher=Amazon.com |accessdate=September 16, 2011}}</ref> and by [[Interscope Records]] on April 5, 2011, in Audio CD format.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rio: Music From the Motion Picture [Soundtrack] |url=https://www.amazon.com/Rio-Motion-Picture-Various-Artists/dp/B004PR71JC |publisher=Amazon.com |accessdate=September 16, 2011}}</ref>\n\n;Track listing\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Performer(s)\n| total_length = 38:11\n| writing_credits = yes\n| title1 = Real in Rio\n| note1 =\n| writer1 = [[S\u00e9rgio Mendes]], [[Carlinhos Brown]], Mikael Mutti, [[John Powell (film composer)|John Powell]], [[Siedah Garrett]]\n| lyrics1 =\n| music1 =\n| extra1 = [[Jesse Eisenberg]], [[Jamie Foxx]], [[Anne Hathaway (actress)|Anne Hathaway]], [[George Lopez]], [[will.i.am]], and The Rio Singers with Hollywood\n| length1 = 3:48\n| title2 = Let Me Take You to Rio (Blu's Arrival)\n| writer2 = [[Ester Dean]], Brown, Mutti\n| extra2 = [[Ester Dean]], and [[Carlinhos Brown]]\n| length2 = 1:54\n| title3 = [[Mas que Nada]]\n| note3 = 2011 ''Rio'' Version\n| writer3 = [[Jorge Ben Jor]]\n| extra3 = [[S\u00e9rgio Mendes]] featuring [[Gracinha Leporace]]\n| length3 = 2:44\n| title4 = Hot Wings (I Wanna Party)\n| writer4 = [[will.i.am]]\n| extra4 = will.i.am, Jamie Foxx, and Anne Hathaway\n| length4 = 2:16\n| title5 = Pretty Bird\n| writer5 = [[Jemaine Clement]], Powell, Yoni Brenner, [[Mike Reiss]]\n| extra5 = [[Jemaine Clement]]\n| length5 = 2:04\n| title6 = Fly Love\n| writer6 = Brown, Garrett\n| extra6 = Jamie Foxx\n| length6 = 2:39\n| title7 = [[Telling the World]]\n| writer7 = [[Taio Cruz]], Alan Kasirye\n| extra7 = [[Taio Cruz]]\n| length7 = 3:33\n| title8 = Funky Monkey\n| writer8 = Garrett, Brown, Mutti\n| extra8 = [[Siedah Garrett]], Carlinhos Brown, Mikael Mutti, and Davi Vieira\n| length8 = 2:24\n| title9 = Take You to Rio\n| note9 = Remix\n| writer9 = Dean, [[Stargate (production team)|Mikkel Storleer Eriksen, Tor Erik Hermansen]]\n| extra9 = Ester Dean\n| length9 = 3:26\n| title10 = Balan\u00e7o Carioca\n| writer10 = Mutti\n| extra10 = Mikael Mutti\n| length10 = 3:01\n| title11 = Sapo Cai\n| writer11 = Brown, Mutti, Mendes\n| extra11 = Carlinhos Brown and Mikael Mutti\n| length11 = 2:46\n| title12 = Samba de Orly\n| writer12 = [[Toquinho]], [[Chico Buarque|Chico Buarque de Hollanda]]\n| extra12 = [[Bebel Gilberto]]\n| length12 = 2:49\n| title13 = Valsa Carioca\n| writer13 = Mendes\n| extra13 = S\u00e9rgio Mendes\n| length13 = 2:35\n| title14 = Forr\u00f3 da Fruta\n| note14  = Bonus Track\n| writer14 = Brown, Mutti\n| extra14 = Carlinhos Brown and Mikael Mutti\n| length14 = 2:12\n}}\n\nIn the Brazilian edition some songs gained a [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] version performed by famous Brazilian artists such [[Ivete Sangalo]] (replacing Ester Dean in \"Take You to Rio (Remix)\") and [[Carlinhos Brown]] (replacing Jamie Foxx in \"Fly Love\"). \"Real in Rio\" became \"Favo de Mel\" (Honeycomb) but it was performed by the same artists as the English version.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rio \u2013 Trilha Sonora Original |url=http://www.saraiva.com.br/rio-trilha-sonora-do-filme-3430152.html/?ID=BD00ED727DB061E0B092F0166 |work=Saraiva.com.br |accessdate=September 16, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Ivete Sangalo sings in the movie Rio soundtrack |url=http://www.ivetesangalo.com/en/2011/05/09/ivete-sangalo-grava-musica-para-trilha-sonora-do-filme-rio |work=Ivete Sangalo |accessdate=September 16, 2011 |date=May 9, 2011}}</ref>\n\n;Track listing\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed       = yes\n| extra_column = Performer(s)\n| total_length = 43:14\n| writing_credits = yes\n| title1 = Favo de Mel (Real in Rio)\n| note1 = \n| writer1 = [[S\u00e9rgio Mendes]], [[Carlinhos Brown]], Mikael Mutti, [[John Powell (film composer)|John Powell]], [[Siedah Garrett]]\n| lyrics1 = \n| music1 = \n| extra1 = [[Jesse Eisenberg]], [[Jamie Foxx]], [[Anne Hathaway (actress)|Anne Hathaway]], [[George Lopez]], [[will.i.am]], and The Rio Singers\n| length1 = 3:48\n| title2 = Let Me Take You to Rio (Blu's Arrival)\n| wri