 = 4:55\n}}\n\n====Charts====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Chart (2011)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n| US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hitsdailydouble.com/sales/salescht.cgi |title=Building Album Sales Chart |work=HITS Daily Double |accessdate=2012-08-07}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|60\n|-\n| US [[Digital Albums]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|10\n|-\n| US ''Billboard'' [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\n|-\n| US ''Billboard'' [[Top Rap Albums]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n| US [[Kid Albums]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|8\n|-\n| US Soundtracks\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|}\n\n===Score===\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Rio\n| type       = Film\n| artist     = [[John Powell (film composer)|John Powell]]\n| cover      =\n| border     = yes\n| alt        = The word \"RIO\" in blue, yellow, and orange letters, with the \"R\" styled to resemble a bird's head.\n| released   = {{Start date|2011|04|19}}\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Film score|Score]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=47|s=04}}\n| label      = [[Var\u00e8se Sarabande]]\n| producer   =\n| chronology = [[John Powell (composer)|John Powell]] film scores\n| prev_title = [[Mars Needs Moms]]\n| prev_year  = 2011\n| next_title = [[Kung Fu Panda 2 (soundtrack)|Kung Fu Panda 2]]\n| next_year  = 2011\n}}\n\nThe [[film score]] of ''Rio'' was composed by [[John Powell (composer)|John Powell]] and was released on April 19, 2011, by [[Var\u00e8se Sarabande Records]].<ref name=\"iTunes\">{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/rio-original-motion-picture/id429214902 |title=Rio (Original Motion Picture Score) |work=iTunes |accessdate=April 22, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"FilmMusicReporter\">{{cite news |url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2011/03/24/rio-score-album-details |accessdate=April 22, 2011 |title='Rio' Score Album Details |newspaper=Film Music Reporter |date=March 24, 2011}}</ref>\n\n;Track listing\n{{Track listing\n| total_length  = 47:04\n| all_writing     = John Powell except where noted\n| title1        = Morning Routine\n| length1       = 2:23\n| title2        = Meet Tulio\n| length2       = 2:55\n| title3        = Great Big Momma Bird\n| length3       = 2:47\n| title4        = Paradise Concern\n| length4       = 1:59\n| title5        = Bagged and Missing\n| length5       = 2:09\n| title6        = Locked Up\n| length6       = 2:10\n| title7        = Chained Chase\n| length7       = 2:35\n| title8        = Bedtime Flyers\n| length8       = 2:58\n| title9        = Idiot Glider\n| length9       = 1:56\n| title10       = Juicy Little Mango\n| length10      = 2:27\n| title11       = Umbrellas of Rio\n| length11      = 2:27\n| title12       = Motorbike\n| length12      = 1:23\n| title13       = Bird Fight\n| length13      = 1:03\n| title14       = Birds Moved\n| length14      = 2:33\n| title15       = Heimlich\n| length15      = 2:31\n| title16       = Birdnapped\n| length16      = 3:37\n| title17       = Rio Airport\n| length17      = 4:24\n| title18       = Flying\n| length18      = 2:43\n| title19       = Market Forro\n| note19        = written by [[Carlinhos Brown]] and Mikael Mutti\n| length19      = 2:11\n}}\n\n==Release==\nThe world premiere of ''Rio'' took place on March 22, 2011, at a [[Cin\u00e9polis]] theater in [[Lagoa, Rio de Janeiro]].<ref name=\"BrazilPremiere\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/animated-3d-film-rio-premieres-in-brazil-favela-2254194.html |title=Animated 3D film 'Rio' premieres in Brazil favela |work=The Independent |location=UK |date=March 26, 2011 |accessdate=June 1, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Lagoa\" /> The United States premiere was on April 10, 2011, at [[Grauman's Chinese Theatre]] in Hollywood, California, and was released throughout the country five days later.<ref name=\"LAPremiere\">{{cite news |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/04/11/last-weekends-events-_n_847623.html |title=Last Weekend's Events: A Red Tie Affair, 'Rio' Premiere, and GLAAD Media Awards |work=Huffington Post |location=USA |date=April 11, 2011 |accessdate=June 1, 2011 |first=Nicole |last=Larson}}</ref> Since May 2009, it had been scheduled to be released in the United States on April 8, 2011, but in December 2010, it was rescheduled a week later to April 15, 2011.<ref>{{cite press release|author1=Twentieth Century Fox|title=New Blue Sky Animated Feature Film Announced \u201cRIO\u201d Opens April 8, 2011|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20090512006239/en/Blue-Sky-Animated-Feature-Film-Announced-%E2%80%9CRIO%E2%80%9D|publisher=Business Wire|accessdate=April 17, 2017|date=May 12, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=New Dates & Changes|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com:80/schedule/?view=changes&p=.htm|publisher=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=April 17, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101225053335/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/schedule/?view=changes&p=.htm|archivedate=December 25, 2010|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Marketing===\nIn April 2011, Oreo announced its special edition Oreo cookies with blue cream in promotion of the film. The promotion included stickers inside each package of cookies. Two types of contest were also announced: first, by completing an album of stickers, consumers could win three movie passes and medium snack bar combos; second, by finding winning stickers in packages with prizes including a trip to Rio de Janeiro, backpacks, cinema passes for a year, and 3D glasses. The promotion ended on May 30, 2011.<ref>{{cite news |title=Concurso Promo Oreo, gana paquetes de cine, viaje a Rio, mochilas y m\u00e1s |url=http://www.pe.promogana.net/2011/04/concurso-promo-oreo-gana-paquetes-de.html |accessdate=September 16, 2011 |newspaper=Promo Gana \u2013 Per\u00fa |date=April 8, 2011}}</ref> The promotion is available in Ecuador, Peru, and Colombia.{{Citation needed|date=August 2012}}\n\nOn January 27, 2011, [[Rovio Entertainment|Rovio Mobile]] announced a partnership with [[20th Century Fox]] to promote the film. The game ''[[Angry Birds Rio]]'' was released in March 2011 on the [[Android Market]] and the [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] [[App Store (iOS)|App Store]] with 50 levels. Rovio released more levels throughout 2011.<ref>{{cite news |last=Warne |first=Alex |title=Angry Birds Going Big Time |url=http://dailynewspulse.com/angry-birds-going-big-time/222346 |accessdate=September 16, 2011 |newspaper=Daily News Pulse |date=January 29, 2011}}</ref> With the DVD and Blu-ray release, Rovio and 20th Century Fox announced that they were going to start selling Rio Plush Toys in the Angry Birds Online Store and the DVD and Blu-ray comes with a code for 15 Hidden Levels, along with 3 Angry Birds Rio Videos. Also, [[McDonald's]] ran a promotion with Rio toys in their Happy Meals.<ref name=\"Angry Birds Rio DVD Bonus Levels and Plush Toys\">{{cite web |last=Team |first=Angry Birds |title=RIO plush toys and DVD wing their way into stores! |url=http://www.rovio.com/index.php?mact=Blogs,cntnt01,showentry,0&cntnt01entryid=78&cntnt01returnid=58 |work=Angry Birds Rio |accessdate=August 3, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2011, the [[Motion Picture Association of America|MPAA]] gave the film a PG rating for \"mild off-color humor\". The producers, displeased by this rating, resubmitted an edited version of the film to the ratings board one month later, and the MPAA changed the film to a G rating.<ref>{{cite news |last=Subers |first=Ray |title=MPAA Ratings: 'Kung Fu Panda 2,' 'Rio,' 'Arthur' and More |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3115&p=.htm |accessdate=September 15, 2011 |newspaper=Box Office Mojo |publisher=IMDb |date=March 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\nAs a tribute to the country where most of the story is set and where the director was born, ''Rio'' was first released for home video in Brazil, on both DVD and [[Blu-ray]], on July 7, 2011.<ref name=\"RioBrazilRelease\">{{cite news |title=Coletiva de imprensa com Carlos Saldanha no Rio de Janeiro |url=https://www.facebook.com/notes/cinnamon-comunica%C3%A7%C3%A3o/coletiva-de-imprensa-com-carlos-saldanha-no-rio-de-janeiro/238908306137596 |accessdate=July 16, 2011 |author=Comunica\u00e7\u00e3o, Cinnamon |date=July 4, 2011 |language=Portuguese}}</ref> The North American release date was August 2, 2011,<ref name=\"ComingSoon\">{{cite news |title=Rio Hits Blu-ray and DVD on August 2 |url=https://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=78672 |accessdate=June 17, 2011 |work=ComingSoon.net |date=June 15, 2011}}</ref> and the Australian release date was September 28, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Podmore|first1=Scott|title=Lively time in vibrant Rio|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/travel/world/lively-time-in-vibrant-rio/news-story/b71366769950e784e9a729487a61d2cb?nk=06baba470b40b5097ac4494c88badc1e-1482776615|website=The Herald Sun|accessdate=26 December 2016}}</ref> As of June 2014, a total of 12 million Blu-ray and DVD units had been sold worldwide.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Graser|first1=Marc|title=Fox Takes Digital Retail Partners on Road for \u2018Rio 2\u2032|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/fox-takes-digital-retail-partners-on-road-for-rio-2-1201246717/|accessdate=June 30, 2014|work=Variety|date=June 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\n''Rio'' is available in 4 different packages: a 4-disc \"Party Edition\" combination package (3D Blu-ray, Blu-ray, DVD, and Digital Copy), a 3-disc \"Party Edition\" combination package (Blu-ray, DVD, and Digital Copy), a 2-disc \"Party Edition\" combination package (DVD and Digital Copy), and a single disc DVD.<ref name=\"ComingSoon\" /><ref name=\"MovieWeb\">{{cite news |last=Gallagher |first=Brian |title=Rio Blu-ray and DVD Arrive August 2nd |url=http://www.movieweb.com/news/rio-blu-ray-and-dvd-arrive-august-2nd |accessdate=June 17, 2011 |work=MovieWeb.com |date=June 15, 2011}}</ref> The \"Digital Copy\" included with the 3-disc combination package is a separate disc that allows users to download a copy of the film to a computer through [[iTunes]] or [[Windows Media Player]] software. The 3-disc combination package also comes with an hour of bonus features.<ref name=\"MovieWeb\" /><ref name=\"Blu-ray.com\">{{cite news |last=Katz |first=Josh |title=Rio Blu-ray |url=http://www.blu-ray.com/news/?id=6676 |accessdate=June 17, 2011 |date=June 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Video games===\n{{Infobox video game\n|title=Rio (video game)\n|image=\n|developer=[[Eurocom]] (Consoles)<br />THQ (DS)\n|director=\n|producer=\n|composer=\n|publisher= [[THQ]]\n|platforms=[[Nintendo DS]], [[PlayStation 3]], [[Wii]], [[Xbox 360]]\n|released= '''Nintendo DS, PlayStation 3, Wii & Xbox 360'''{{vgrelease|NA|April 12, 2011|AUS|April 7, 2011|EU|April 8, 2011}}\n|modes= [[Single-player]], [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]]\n|genre= [[Party video game|Party]] <br />[[Music video games|Musical Platform]] (Nintendo DS)\n}}\nA video game based on the film was released on April 12, 2011, by THQ, for the [[Wii]], [[Nintendo DS]], [[PlayStation 3]], and the [[Xbox 360]].<ref name=\"GameStop\">{{cite web |title=Rio by THQ |url=http://www.gamestop.com/xbox-360/games/rio/90273 |work=Rio |accessdate=July 14, 2011}}</ref> Another game, ''[[Angry Birds Rio]]'', was released in March 2011 for various mobile and desktop systems.<ref name=\"ABRio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/218181/angry_birds_rio_release_teams_with_hollywood.html|title='Angry Birds Rio' Release Teams With Hollywood|author=Paul Suarez|work=PCWorld.com|date=2011-01-29|accessdate=2011-02-04| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110205124337/http://www.pcworld.com/article/218181/angry_birds_rio_release_teams_with_hollywood.html| archivedate=February 5, 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n====Reception (Rio)====\nThe game received mixed reception, with, for lowest to highest, Metacritic at 60 out of 100 based on 16 reviews for the Xbox 360 version,<ref>https://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-360/rio</ref> and 65 out of 100 based on 8 reviews for the PlayStation 3 version.<ref>https://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-3/rio</ref> And in GameRankings, 40.00% for the Wii version, 58.00% for the Nintendo DS version, 64.73% for the Xbox 360 version, and 71.67% for the PlayStation 3.\n\n==Rio: The 4-D Experience==\n''Rio: The 4-D Experience'' is a 12-minute [[4D film]] shown at various 4-D theatres over the world. Produced by [[SimEx-Iwerks]], it premiered on September 27, 2013 at the [[San Diego Zoo]] 4-D Theater.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sandiegozoo.org/rio/|title=Rio The 4-D Experience|website=San Diego Zoo}}</ref> Since May 24, 2014, it is being shown at the 5D Cinema at the revived [[Kentucky Kingdom]]. Since July 2014, it is being shown at the 4D Special FX Theater at [[Moody Gardens]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.moodygardens.com/attractions/4d_special_fx_theater/4d_schedule/|title=Virtual Reality Theater - 4D Special FX Theater - Interactive Movie Theater - Special Effects Theaters|website=www.moodygardens.com}}</ref> And since October 25, 2014, it is being shown at the [[Roxy Theatre (Warner Bros. Movie World)|Roxy Theatre]] at [[Warner Bros. Movie World]].<ref>movieworld.com.au/rides-and-attractions/family-entertainment/rio-4d.aspx</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''Rio'' made $143,619,809 in North America, along with $341,015,951 in other territories for a total of $484,635,760 worldwide, becoming the 13th highest-grossing film of 2011<ref>{{cite web |title=2011 WORLDWIDE GROSSES |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?view2=worldwide&yr=2011&p=.htm |work=Box Office Mojo |publisher=IMDb |accessdate=April 23, 2012}}</ref> and the 107th highest-grossing film of all time.<ref name=\"BoxOfficeMojo\">{{cite web |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=rio.htm |title=Rio (2011) |work=Box Office Mojo |publisher=IMDb |accessdate=September 2, 2011}}</ref> It was the first film of 2011 to pass the $400-million mark.\n\n====North America====\n''Rio'' debuted with $39,225,962 during its opening weekend on approximately 6,400 screens at 3,826 theaters. It ranked No. 1 at the box office surpassing the other new wide release, ''[[Scream 4]]'', which ranked #2.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3142&p=.htm |title=Weekend Report: 'Rio' Leads, 'Scream' Bleeds |first=Brandon |last=Gray |publisher=IMDb |work=Box Office Mojo |date=April 17, 2011 |accessdate=April 18, 2011}}</ref> This was the highest-grossing opening weekend of 2011 that far, finishing the year at sixteenth.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?view2=opening&yr=2011&p=.htm |title=2011 OPENING GROSSES |publisher=IMDb |work=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=April 18, 2011}}</ref> It also scored the largest opening weekend in April for an animated feature, and the sixth largest in April overall.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/alltime/weekends/month/?mo=04&p=.htm |title=TOP OPENING WEEKENDS BY MONTH |publisher=IMDb |work=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=June 8, 2011}}</ref> On its second weekend (Easter weekend) it retained first place at the box office, dropping only 33% to $26.3 million, therefore surpassing that weekend's releases, Tyler Perry's ''[[Madea's Big Happy Family (film)|Madea's Big Happy Family]]'' ($25.1 million), ''[[Water for Elephants (film)|Water for Elephants]]'' ($16.8 million), and ''[[African Cats]]'' ($6 million), which ranked second, third, and sixth, respectively.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?view=&yr=2011&wknd=16&p=.htm |title=April 22\u201324, 2011 Weekend |publisher=IMDb |work=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=April 18, 2011}}</ref> ''Rio''{{'}}s income of $143.6 million made it Blue Sky's second lowest box office result at the time, surpassing only ''[[Robots (2005 film)|Robots]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3165&p=.htm|title=Animation Deceptively Strong So Far in 2011 - Box Office Mojo|website=boxofficemojo.com}}</ref> and the 18th highest-grossing film of the year in North America.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?yr=2011&p=.htm|title=2011 Yearly Box Office Results - Box Office Mojo|website=boxofficemojo.com}}</ref>\n\n====Other territories====\nOn its first weekend overseas (the weekend before its release in North America) it topped the box office with $54.9 million from 11,714 screens in 72 countries.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3136&p=.htm |title=Around-the-World Roundup: 'Rio' Livens Up Foreign Box Office |first=Ray |last=Subers |publisher=IMDb |work=Box Office Mojo |date=April 13, 2011 |accessdate=April 25, 2011}}</ref> On its second weekend it earned $55.4 million, still on top of the overseas box office<ref>{{cite news |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3144&p=.htm |title=Around-the-World Roundup: 'Rio' Continues to Soar Overseas |first=Ray |last=Subers |publisher=IMDb |work=Box Office Mojo |date=April 17, 2011 |accessdate=April 25, 2011}}</ref> and on its third weekend it remained at the summit of the box office, grossing an estimated $44.3 million. It therefore marked the second film that succeeded in topping the overseas box office three times in 2011, joining ''[[Tangled]]'', although it is the only one that did it on three consecutive weekends.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3147&p=.htm |title=Around-the-World Roundup: 'Rio' Reigns Again, 'Fast Five,' 'Thor' Duke It Out in Australia |first=Ray |last=Subers |publisher=IMDb |work=Box Office Mojo |date=April 26, 2011 |accessdate=April 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn Brazil, the film's main setting and Saldanha's homeland, ''Rio'' was the largest release ever with over 1,000 screens.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fox confirma estreia recorde de \"Rio\" no Brasi|url=http://ultimosegundo.ig.com.br/cultura/cinema/fox+confirma+estreia+recorde+de+rio+no+brasil/n1300033422291.html|publisher=Ultimo Segundo|accessdate=March 31, 2014|date=April 7, 2011}}</ref> Its opening weekend gross of $8.4 million was the biggest ever for an American film<ref>{{cite news |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3136&p=.htm |title=Around-the-World Roundup: 'Rio' Livens Up Foreign Box Office |first=Ray |last=Subers |publisher=IMDb |work=Box Office Mojo |date=April 13, 2011 |accessdate=April 18, 2011}}</ref> (surpassed one year later by ''[[Madagascar 3: Europe's Most Wanted]]''). On its second weekend it earned $7.2 million, falling just 14% from its opening. It then delivered the highest-grossing third weekend in history with $6.3 million (a 12% decline).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3147&p=.htm |title=Around-the-World Roundup: 'Rio' Reigns Again, 'Fast Five,' 'Thor' Duke It Out in Australia |first=Brandon |last=Gray |publisher=IMDb |work=Box Office Mojo |date=April 26, 2011 |accessdate=May 4, 2011}}</ref> ''Rio'' finished 2011 with a final gross of $36.8 million (R$68.7 million), the second highest income of the year after ''[[The Twilight Saga: Breaking Dawn \u2013 Part 1]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://oca.ancine.gov.br/media/SAM/Informes/2011/Informe_Anual_2011.pdf |title=INFORME DE  ACOMPANHAMENTO DO MERCADO: Filmes e Bilheterias, Resultados de 2011  |publisher=Ancine|language=Portuguese|format=PDF|page=6|date=January 11, 2012|accessdate=March 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Russia]] and the [[Commonwealth of Independent States|CIS]], it topped the box office with $11.3 million during its opening weekend (including weekday previews), surpassing ''Tangled'' for the largest all-time opening of a non-sequel animated feature. It earned $24.7 million in total, marking the fourth largest animated film of all time.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/intl/cis/yearly |title=Russia Box Office |publisher=IMDb |work=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=June 8, 2011}}</ref> In [[Venezuela]], it has earned $8 million, marking the second-highest-grossing film of all time behind ''Ice Age 3'' ($11.6 million).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/intl/venezuela/yearly/?yr=2011&p=.htm |title=Venezuela Yearly Box Office |publisher=IMDb |work=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=June 16, 2011}}</ref> In [[Uruguay]], it is the fourth highest-grossing film of all time with $754,820 after ''[[Titanic (1997 film)|Titanic]]'' ($2.1 million), ''[[Avatar (2009 film)|Avatar]]'' ($1.1 million), and ''Ice Age 3'' ($1 million).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/intl/uruguay/yearly/?yr=2011&p=.htm |title=Uruguay Yearly Box Office |publisher=IMDb |work=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=June 16, 2011}}</ref> In [[Peru]], grossing $3.8 million, it is the third-largest animated feature behind ''Ice Age 3'' and ''[[Shrek Forever After]]'', and the fourth highest-grossing film of all time behind these two and ''Avatar''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/intl/peru/yearly/?yr=2011&p=.htm |title=Peru Yearly Box Office |publisher=IMDb |work=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=June 16, 2011}}</ref> In [[India]], it grossed {{INR}}10,000,000 in three weeks making the biggest animated opener ever.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficeindia.co.in/rio-rises-to-greater-heights |title=Rio gets to Greater heights |publisher=Box Office India |accessdate=August 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n{{Anchor|Critics}}\n''Rio'' received positive reviews from film critics. The review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives the film a 72% rating based on 148 reviews, with an average rating of 6.4/10. The website's consensus is: \"This straightforward movie hits great heights thanks to its colorful visual palette, catchy music, and perfect vocal performances.\"<ref name=\"RottenTomatoes\" /> On [[Metacritic]], which assigns a normalized rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the film has an average score of 63 out of 100, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/rio |title=Rio |work=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=April 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[Owen Gleiberman]] of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave the film a mixed \"C\" rating; he praised the animation in ''Rio'' and its music, but later went on to say that the film is \"less a [[Pixar]]-level pleasure than a busy, frantic, and overstuffed dessert of a movie.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20481533,00.html |title=Rio |last=Gleiberman |first=Owen |work=Entertainment Weekly |accessdate=April 13, 2011}}</ref> Betsy Sharkey of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' gave the film a positive review, praising its comic action, voices and visuals.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2011/apr/15/entertainment/la-et-rio-20110415 |title='Rio' review |last=Sharkey |first=Betsy |work=Los Angeles Times |date=April 15, 2011 |accessdate=May 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=\"99%\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; vertical-align:bottom;\"\n|+ style=\"background: LightSteelBlue;\" | List of awards and nominations\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! Award\n! Category\n! Recipient(s)\n! Result\n|- style=\"border-top:2px solid gray;\"\n|-\n|-\n| [[84th Academy Awards]]\n| [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]], \"Real in Rio\"\n| [[S\u00e9rgio Mendes]]<br />[[Carlinhos Brown]]<br />[[Siedah Garrett]]\n| rowspan=2 {{Nom}}\n|-\n| style=\"border-top:10px black\" rowspan=\"8\" | [[Annie Award]]s\n| [[Annie Award for Best Animated Feature|Best Animated Feature]]\n| Bruce Anderson<br /> John C. Donkin\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Annie Award#Individual achievement|Best Character Animation in an Animated Production]]\n| Jeff Gabor\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Patrik Puhala\n| rowspan=11 {{Nom}}\n|-\n| [[Annie Award#Individual achievement|Best Character Design in a Feature Production]]\n| Sergios Pablos\n|-\n| [[Annie Award#Individual achievement|Directing in an Animated Feature Production]]\n| [[Carlos Saldanha]]\n|-\n| [[Annie Award#Individual achievement|Best Music in